You have to look at the frontier and threads reports to better 
understand the state.

With default settings, there&#39;s one queue per hostname. When a queue is 
empty, there&#39;s nothing left to crawl from that hostname.

The &#39;parallelQueues&#39; setting you asked about last week will spread a 
hostname&#39;s URIs over multiple queues, and thus allow multiple threads to 
be collecting URIs in parallel. But it&#39;s not yet clear that&#39;s your 
problem; even one thread fetching as fast as possible (no politeness 
&#39;snoozes&#39;) may fully load your target server, and so adding more threads 
may just mean they&#39;re competing against themselves (for little if any 
speedup).

- Gordon @ IA

On 12/27/10 5:02 AM, yotpo.official wrote:
&gt; What is the reason for this?
&gt; I am crawling only my own site and there are no politeness considerations,in this way it will take my for ages to index my site... What can I do to make all 10 threads and queues functional?
&gt; Thank you
&gt;
&gt; --- In archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com, Gordon Mohr&lt;gojomo@...&gt;  wrote:
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; This is a wholly normal state for a crawl that&#39;s still working on one queue.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; &quot;10 exhausted&quot; means that 10 queues once had URIs in them, but finished.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; &quot;1 in-process&quot; means one queue has offered up a URI which is in the
&gt;&gt; middle of a processing cycle. Looking at the frontier report will reveal
&gt;&gt; which queue offered the URI, the count of other URIs in that queue, and
&gt;&gt; other details. Looking at the threads report will reveal the processor
&gt;&gt; currently working on the in-process URI.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; With a single queue still holding URIs, and normal politeness settings,
&gt;&gt; you would expect on subsequent viewings of this summary to see the queue
&gt;&gt; bouncing from &#39;in-process&#39; to &#39;snoozed&#39; and back, until the queue is
&gt;&gt; exhausted. If occasionally new URIs are discovered on other hosts, other
&gt;&gt; queues might reenter active crawling as well.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; - Gordon @ IA
